ocess where products produced are not separately identifiable until this point. Costs incurred before the SOP are joint costs.\"", "\"FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION\":\"An example where two products, G and H, are created from a joint process. G can be sold immediately after split-off, while H requires further processing. The decision to further process H is based on comparing additional revenue against additional costs.\"", "\"QUIZ: FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION\":\"The quiz involves determining whether Daisy Co should further process a chemical into two components, A and B, based on their sales value and allocated costs.\"", "\"FOXGLOVE CO\":\"Foxglove Co is the company involved in the production line closure decision quiz.\"", "\"DAISY CO\":\"Daisy Co is the company involved in the further processing decision quiz.\"", "\"PRODUCT G\":\"Product G is one of the products created from a joint process and can be sold immediately after the split-off point.\"", "\"PRODUCT H\":Product H is a product with the second highest contribution per limiting factor, to be produced after Product I until the limiting factor is used up. It is one of the products created from a joint process and requires further processing before it can be sold.", "\"PRODUCT A\":Product A is a versatile product associated with multiple companies. It is one of the components resulting from further processing a chemical in the Daisy Co quiz. Additionally, Product A is manufactured by Yam Co, where it has a selling price of $70, a raw materials cost of $3, a labor cost of $10, and requires 0.5 hours of pressing time per unit. Furthermore, Product A is also made and sold by Flopro, with specific costs and a selling price, although these details are not explicitly provided.", "\"PRODUCT B\":Product B is a product made and sold by Flopro, with specific costs and a selling price. It is one of the components resulting from further processing a chemical in the Daisy Co quiz. Additionally, Product B is manufactured by Yam Co. It has a selling price of $60, a raw materials cost of $2.5, a labor cost of $10, and a pressing time per unit of 0.5 hours.", "\"FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION QUIZ\":\"Quiz: Further Processing Decision. Daisy Co buys a chemical for $12,000, which is broken down into two components. The quiz requires determining the optimal production plan to maximize profits.\"", "\"OUTSOURCING\":Outsourcing involves contracting out certain business activities or functions to external providers rather than producing or providing them internally. This practice can encompass a wide range of services, including office cleaning, canteen and catering services, payroll services, IT services, and security services. Companies may choose to outsource for various reasons, such as cost savings in the long run or to achieve higher quality, even if the cost of outsourcing is higher. For example, a company might contract a third-party supplier in Burgistan to produce keypads and display screens instead of manufacturing them in-house, comparing the cost of buying from the supplier to the in-house production costs.", "\"ADVANTAGES OF OUTSOURCING\":\"Advantages of outsourcing include lower cost, services becoming a variable cost, management focus on core competencies, higher quality from specialist suppliers, and access to a broader range of expertise.\"", "\"DISADVANTAGES OF OUTSOURCING\":\"Disadvantages of outsourcing include reliance on a third party, loss of control, hidden costs, potential quality issues, operational dependence on the outsourcing company's financial stability, and potential workforce demotivation.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}